WEBVTT

00:06.240 --> 00:09.843
JUDY WOODRUFF: Good evening. I'm
Judy Woodruff. Gwen Ifill is
away.

00:09.843 --> 00:15.082
On the "NewsHour" tonight:
Investigators conclude a
Russian-made missile took down
the Malaysia

00:15.082 --> 00:18.452
Airlines flight over
Ukraine last year.

00:18.452 --> 00:24.057
Then: Democrats running for
president get their first crack
at the debate stage tonight.

00:24.057 --> 00:28.896
Plus, our series called Congo's
hope continues, with a look at
how cinema can help heal the

00:28.896 --> 00:31.031
wounds of war.

00:31.031 --> 00:33.533
CHERIE RIVERS NDALIKO, Executive
Director, Yole!Africa: It's
incredible to see what happens

00:33.533 --> 00:35.402
when they learn that they can
tell their own story, and in
their version of the story,

00:35.402 --> 00:38.238
they can be the hero.

00:38.238 --> 00:43.410
JUDY WOODRUFF: And the last of
the president's men. I talk with
Bob Woodward and Alexander

00:43.410 --> 00:48.115
Butterfield about the new book
that reveals new dimensions of
Richard Nixon's personality

00:48.115 --> 00:50.250
and his obsession with secrecy.

00:50.250 --> 00:57.457
All that and more on
tonight's "PBS NewsHour."

00:57.457 --> 01:01.995
(BREAK)

01:01.995 --> 01:12.506
JUDY WOODRUFF: Palestinians
proclaimed today a day of rage
after nearly a month of
escalating

01:12.506 --> 01:18.478
violence. Three Israeli
civilians died in a string of
stabbing attacks, along with
three

01:18.478 --> 01:22.049
Palestinians, including two of
the attackers. In response,
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin

01:22.049 --> 01:27.054
Netanyahu called an
emergency Cabinet meeting.

01:27.054 --> 01:33.360
There is word that U.S. and
Russian jets flew within miles
of each other over Syria on
Saturday.

01:33.360 --> 01:38.065
The Pentagon reported the
incident today in a video
briefing. Russian airstrikes
have

01:38.065 --> 01:42.402
been hammering targets across
Syria. A U.S. military spokesman
says the close encounter

01:42.402 --> 01:44.738
underscores the risk.

01:44.738 --> 01:48.475
COL. STEVE WARREN, U.S. Army: It
is dangerous, right? I mean,
it's dangerous if two sets

01:48.475 --> 01:55.115
of aircraft come into the same
piece of airspace without very
clear, laid-out protocols for

01:55.115 --> 01:59.720
safety of all involved, which is
why we have sat down with the
Russians to establish some

01:59.720 --> 02:01.588
safety protocols.

02:01.588 --> 02:06.860
JUDY WOODRUFF: Meanwhile, at a
Moscow event, President Vladimir
Putin blamed Washington

02:06.860 --> 02:11.131
for a lack of coordination on
the competing air campaigns.

02:11.131 --> 02:17.137
VLADIMIR PUTIN, Russian
President (through translator):
We asked the U.S. on the
military

02:17.137 --> 02:20.374
level to give us the targets
which they consider to be the
terrorist ones. But the answer
was,

02:20.374 --> 02:23.510
no, we are not ready to do that.

02:23.510 --> 02:26.013
Then we thought and asked
another question. Could you tell
us where we shouldn't hit?

02:26.013 --> 02:29.983
Again, no answer. So,
what should we do?

02:29.983 --> 02:35.489
JUDY WOODRUFF: The next round of
talks between the U.S. and
Russian militaries will be
tomorrow.

02:35.489 --> 02:40.594
Meanwhile, the Islamic State
called today for Muslims to
launch a holy war against both

02:40.594 --> 02:45.399
countries. The appeal was in an
audio message posted online.

02:45.399 --> 02:50.604
In Afghanistan, the Taliban
announced it's pulling back from
Kunduz, the city in the

02:50.604 --> 02:56.410
north, to avoid further civilian
casualties. Taliban fighters
held Kunduz for three days

02:56.410 --> 03:01.915
last month, and the fierce
fighting forced thousands of
people to flee. Now fighting

03:01.915 --> 03:08.255
has shifted south to Ghazni, a
city that lies along the main
highway between Kabul and
Kandahar.

03:08.255 --> 03:13.960
Iran's Parliament voted today to
approve a nuclear deal with the
U.S. and other world

03:13.960 --> 03:20.567
powers. It came after rowdy
debate and objections from
hard-liners, who argued the deal
concedes

03:20.567 --> 03:26.373
too much to the West. Now the
bill goes to the Guardian
Council of 12 clerics for
ratification.

03:26.373 --> 03:31.678
The stance of Supreme Leader
Ayatollah Ali Khamenei is still
unknown. He has the final

03:31.678 --> 03:36.316
say on all matters of state.

03:36.316 --> 03:42.189
The world's top two beer makers
are joining forces.
Anheuser-Busch InBev sealed a
deal

03:42.189 --> 03:49.463
today to buy SABMiller for $106
billion. In a company video, the
head of A.B. InBev said

03:49.463 --> 03:52.365
it's all about consumer choice.

03:52.365 --> 03:55.068
CARLOS BRITO, CEO,
Anheuser-Busch InBev: Our joint
portfolio of global and local
brands

03:55.068 --> 04:00.774
would provide more choices for
beer drinkers in new and
existing markets around the
world.

04:00.774 --> 04:05.345
Consumers would have more
opportunities to taste a wide
range of beers, ranging from

04:05.345 --> 04:10.784
specialty and craft beers to
local champions and global
flagship brands.

04:10.784 --> 04:15.689
JUDY WOODRUFF: The new company
will control about a third of
the global beer market. But

04:15.689 --> 04:19.092
the sheer size of the deal could
run into resistance from
regulators, especially in

04:19.092 --> 04:22.729
the U.S. and China.

04:22.729 --> 04:27.701
And Wall Street had a down day
after China reported that its
imports fell 20 percent

04:27.701 --> 04:32.706
last month over a year ago. The
Dow Jones industrial average
lost 50 points to close

04:32.706 --> 04:40.914
back near 17080. The Nasdaq fell
42 points and the S&P 500
dropped 13.

04:40.914 --> 04:45.819
Still to come on the "NewsHour":
digging into the evidence of
what shot down the Malaysian

04:45.819 --> 04:52.792
passenger plane over Ukraine;
how a possible Joe Biden run
could influence tonight's
Democratic

04:52.792 --> 04:57.430
debate; a new book reveals
untold dimensions of President
Nixon's White House, and much

04:57.430 --> 05:05.539
more.

05:05.539 --> 05:16.816
A 15-month-long investigation
into what brought down Malaysia
Airlines Flight 17 last year

05:16.816 --> 05:22.756
is over. And, as most expected,
it concluded a missile targeted
the plane. The airliner

05:22.756 --> 05:28.595
was traveling from Amsterdam to
Kuala Lumpur when it was struck
over Eastern Ukraine. No

05:28.595 --> 05:36.002
one has taken responsibility,
but today's report set sharpened
suspicions and denials.

05:36.002 --> 05:42.275
Like a giant jigsaw puzzle, the
pieced-together wreckage of the
plane's front fuselage loomed

05:42.275 --> 05:46.680
over the chairman of the Dutch
Safety Board, as he announced
the findings:

05:46.680 --> 05:50.750
TJIBBE JOUSTRA, Dutch Safety
Board Chairman: Flight MH17
crashed as a result of the
detonation

05:50.750 --> 05:56.156
of a warhead outside the
airplane, above the left-hand
side of the cockpit.

05:56.156 --> 06:01.962
JUDY WOODRUFF: In short, as this
Dutch animation depicts, a
Russian-built missile,
identified

06:01.962 --> 06:09.703
by shrapnel and paint, blew the
Malaysian airliner apart on July
17 last year. The report

06:09.703 --> 06:13.873
says the missile exploded less
than a meter from the cockpit,
spraying metal fragments

06:13.873 --> 06:16.776
into the plane.

06:16.776 --> 06:24.517
All 298 people on board were
killed, as wreckage, luggage and
bodies rained down over Eastern

06:24.517 --> 06:30.090
Ukraine. Investigators say some
passengers might have stayed
alive for a minute or so

06:30.090 --> 06:36.563
after impact, but were too dazed
by shock, cold and loss of
oxygen to know what was
happening.

06:36.563 --> 06:39.666
Barry Sweeney's son was
one of those who died.

06:39.666 --> 06:44.971
BARRY SWEENEY, Father of Victim:
But because of the impact of the
missile, the explosion,

06:44.971 --> 06:49.175
the confusion and everything
else, it sounds as though
everybody died peacefully. And
that's

06:49.175 --> 06:54.614
comforting me, and I would think
all other families of Flight
MH17.

06:54.614 --> 07:00.654
JUDY WOODRUFF: The investigation
also plotted simulated flight
paths and concluded the missile

07:00.654 --> 07:07.027
was launched from a
124-square-mile region.
Russian-backed separatists
controlled that

07:07.027 --> 07:13.133
area, but the report doesn't
address who fired the weapon.
Still, the Russian state arms

07:13.133 --> 07:18.405
producer that makes the BUK
missile disputed those findings.
It said its own experiments

07:18.405 --> 07:22.042
prove a much older missile
took down the plane.

07:22.042 --> 07:24.711
YAN NOVIKOV, General Director,
Almaz-Antey (through
translator): The general
engineer

07:24.711 --> 07:30.250
of missile 9M38 decided that the
safety period for using this
missile, including all
extensions,

07:30.250 --> 07:34.688
is 25 years. The use of these
missiles was prohibited after
that, and they were retired

07:34.688 --> 07:37.090
from the Russian army.

07:37.090 --> 07:42.162
JUDY WOODRUFF: The arms
manufacturer said that kind of
missile is still used by
Ukraine's

07:42.162 --> 07:47.834
military and that, in fact, it
was launched from
Ukrainian-controlled territory.
Either

07:47.834 --> 07:51.604
way, the Dutch investigators
said today the plane never
should have been in that
airspace

07:51.604 --> 07:54.040
to begin with.

07:54.040 --> 07:58.712
TJIBBE JOUSTRA: Ukraine's
position is that there was
insufficient reason for closing

07:58.712 --> 08:04.884
the airspace above the eastern
part of the country. We have,
however, concluded that,

08:04.884 --> 08:09.756
as a precaution, there was
sufficient reason for Ukraine
authorities to close the
airspace

08:09.756 --> 08:12.459
above the eastern part
of their country.

08:12.459 --> 08:16.730
JUDY WOODRUFF: Meanwhile, Dutch
prosecutors say unnamed persons
of interest have been

08:16.730 --> 08:21.901
identified in a criminal
investigation that is
continuing.

08:21.901 --> 08:26.573
We look at some of the details
of today's findings with a
longtime investigator. Peter

08:26.573 --> 08:31.878
Goelz is a former managing
director of the U.S. National
Transportation Safety Board.

08:31.878 --> 08:37.384
He oversaw the investigation,
among others, of TWA Flight 800
that crashed off Long Island

08:37.384 --> 08:41.388
almost 20 years ago and
speculation then of whether a
missile brought it down.

08:41.388 --> 08:44.824
Peter Goelz, welcome
back to the program.

08:44.824 --> 08:48.294
How good a job did this
international team do, do you
think, of piecing together what

08:48.294 --> 08:50.363
caused this crash?

08:50.363 --> 08:51.598
PETER GOELZ, Former Managing
Director, National
Transportation Safety Board: I
think they

08:51.598 --> 08:56.369
did an extraordinary job. I read
the report late last night and
this morning. It's almost

08:56.369 --> 09:02.609
300 pages in length. It is
detailed. It is factual. And
it's very sober.

09:02.609 --> 09:08.314
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, among other
things, I'm struck by how it
describes pieces of shrapnel

09:08.314 --> 09:14.587
from this missile, paint from
the missile embedded in the
bodies of the crew and people

09:14.587 --> 09:18.625
who were sitting in the front of
the plane. Does it leave any
doubt of the kind of missile

09:18.625 --> 09:23.496
that hit right at the -- what
they said, a meter from the
plane?

09:23.496 --> 09:27.801
PETER GOELZ: Yes, no, there's no
doubt about the type of missile
or where it struck.

09:27.801 --> 09:35.809
I mean, when a missile detonates
in that proximity to the
aircraft, it leaves very
distinctive

09:35.809 --> 09:41.214
marks, as you can see, on the
nose of the aircraft. And these
holes, these hundreds

09:41.214 --> 09:47.487
of holes, they have microscopic
bits of the metal, of the piece
of shrapnel sometimes

09:47.487 --> 09:51.825
in the hole. And you can
trace it back to the source.

09:51.825 --> 10:00.400
JUDY WOODRUFF: And we heard the
Dutch investigator call it the
9N314 missile. What does it tell

10:00.400 --> 10:06.406
you, Peter Goelz, that is a
missile that blew up just
outside the plane? It didn't hit
the

10:06.406 --> 10:09.375
plane. It blew up before
it struck the plane.

10:09.375 --> 10:14.948
PETER GOELZ: Now, the more
recent missiles have what they
call proximity fuses. And they

10:14.948 --> 10:20.386
are driven by radar. It senses
when they're in close proximity
to their target and they

10:20.386 --> 10:27.460
explode and dispersing the
shrapnel in a very defined way.

10:27.460 --> 10:36.769
We did tests in 1997 at the
China Lake Missile Center in
which the U.S., we detonated
warheads

10:36.769 --> 10:43.176
near pieces of aircraft skin,
the metal, the aluminum. And we
saw the very distinctive

10:43.176 --> 10:47.981
patterns that they left. So the
investigators knew what they
were looking for and knew what

10:47.981 --> 10:50.450
they had when they found it.

10:50.450 --> 10:55.688
JUDY WOODRUFF: It is possible to
say one side or another would
have had this kind of missile?

10:55.688 --> 10:59.192
We know the Russians are saying,
no, we don't have this missile
in our arsenal anymore;

10:59.192 --> 11:02.095
the Ukrainians were using this.

11:02.095 --> 11:08.101
PETER GOELZ: Well, I think that
the investigators that I have
spoken to who were involved in

11:08.101 --> 11:16.276
this time-consuming effort have
indicated that there is other
information available

11:16.276 --> 11:21.214
from intelligence sources that
indicate where this missile was
launched from, and that it's

11:21.214 --> 11:25.952
very clear that it was well
inside the separatist territory.

11:25.952 --> 11:30.423
JUDY WOODRUFF: So is it
possible, do you think it will
eventually be possible to say
this

11:30.423 --> 11:33.192
was the source, this is
who fired that missile?

11:33.192 --> 11:36.663
PETER GOELZ: Yes, I think
the truth comes out.

11:36.663 --> 11:44.470
After KAL 007 was shot down off
the Soviet Union, it took years,
and it took years of

11:44.470 --> 11:50.109
activism on the part of family
members, but eventually the
Russians admitted what happened.

11:50.109 --> 11:54.414
I think it will take time, but
the truth will come out in this
case as well.

11:54.414 --> 11:58.217
JUDY WOODRUFF: And one other
thing, the discussion today
about whether this plane,
passenger

11:58.217 --> 12:02.255
plane should have been flying
over an area of conflict?

12:02.255 --> 12:06.826
PETER GOELZ: That is probably
the most important
recommendation that the Dutch
made. You know,

12:06.826 --> 12:11.698
that day, there had been almost
150 aircraft traveling along
that airway, the same one

12:11.698 --> 12:12.231
that Malaysia...

12:12.231 --> 12:13.633
JUDY WOODRUFF: Passenger planes.

12:13.633 --> 12:16.903
PETER GOELZ: That's right.
These are passengers planes.

12:16.903 --> 12:22.175
And what they said was that
there was very poor coordination
between the civil aviation

12:22.175 --> 12:27.814
authorities and the government,
and the governments at play, and
that they probably shouldn't

12:27.814 --> 12:33.553
have been there in that area of
conflict, because planes at
lower altitudes, mind you,

12:33.553 --> 12:39.225
had been being shot down, that
greater attention has to be paid
to the safety of the airways.

12:39.225 --> 12:43.096
JUDY WOODRUFF: Peter Goelz,
we thank you very much.

12:43.096 --> 12:53.973
PETER GOELZ: Thank you.

12:53.973 --> 13:02.715
JUDY WOODRUFF: We will hear a
great deal from the five
Democrats vying to be president
tonight,

13:02.715 --> 13:07.186
as they take to the debate stage
for the first time in this
campaign.

13:07.186 --> 13:10.757
But hovering over them are
questions about a potential
sixth candidate, Vice President

13:10.757 --> 13:13.726
Joe Biden.

13:13.726 --> 13:16.696
Some Democrats are getting
impatient and say it's time for
him to decide whether or not

13:16.696 --> 13:18.998
he's going to run.

13:18.998 --> 13:22.568
The "NewsHour"'s political
director, Lisa Desjardins,
reports from Las Vegas on the

13:22.568 --> 13:24.570
Biden factor.

13:24.570 --> 13:28.975
LISA DESJARDINS: The man
not on stage tonight...

13:28.975 --> 13:30.376
JOSEPH BIDEN, Vice President of
the United States: I'm Joe
Biden. I'm Jill's husband.

13:30.376 --> 13:35.014
LISA DESJARDINS: ... has had
plenty to stay this month. Going
off script at a Hispanic

13:35.014 --> 13:39.452
heritage event, he took aim at
Donald Trump and Republicans on
immigration.

13:39.452 --> 13:43.923
JOSEPH BIDEN: Trump and that
stuff you're hearing on the
other team, and not just -- this

13:43.923 --> 13:48.428
isn't about Democrat/Republican.
It's about a sick message.

13:48.428 --> 13:53.066
LISA DESJARDINS: With union
workers on Labor Day, he went
after tax breaks for the rich.

13:53.066 --> 13:59.472
JOSEPH BIDEN: Why in God's name
should a man or woman working in
a steel mill making $50,000

13:59.472 --> 14:02.942
a year pay at a higher rate than
someone who makes tens of
millions of dollars on Wall

14:02.942 --> 14:04.477
Street?

14:04.477 --> 14:07.947
LISA DESJARDINS: And at a solar
convention, it was climate.

14:07.947 --> 14:13.152
JOSEPH BIDEN: Make no mistake
about it, folks, climate change
is caused by human endeavors,

14:13.152 --> 14:20.259
and it's an existential threat.
What's at stake is whether we
have a future at all.

14:20.259 --> 14:26.232
LISA DESJARDINS: The topics and
tone of a candidate, they are
from a man on pause. Biden,

14:26.232 --> 14:30.670
who has been mourning the death
of his son Beau, told "The Late
Show"'s Stephen Colbert

14:30.670 --> 14:33.840
he's not sure he has the heart
to run for the White House
again.

14:33.840 --> 14:40.246
JOSEPH BIDEN: I would be lying
if I said that I knew I was
there.

14:40.246 --> 14:44.183
LISA DESJARDINS: As Biden
carefully considers whether to
enter the race, Democratic
voters

14:44.183 --> 14:49.155
and funders will be focused on
the debate stage here in Las
Vegas tonight and the declared

14:49.155 --> 14:52.525
candidates, and some political
experts say Biden's window to
jump in the race may be

14:52.525 --> 14:54.393
finite.

14:54.393 --> 14:56.863
HILARY ROSEN, Democratic
Strategist: He doesn't have a
long time. But he's got several
weeks

14:56.863 --> 14:58.064
more.

14:58.064 --> 15:00.900
LISA DESJARDINS: Hilary Rosen
is a Democratic strategist.

15:00.900 --> 15:05.438
HILARY ROSEN: There are some
filing deadlines I think coming
up next month that he has to

15:05.438 --> 15:10.777
deal with. But we're going to
have a debate a month for the
next six months. He's got

15:10.777 --> 15:13.045
to get in.

15:13.045 --> 15:17.950
LISA DESJARDINS: What would it
mean if Biden gets in? Here's a
look at how those on stage

15:17.950 --> 15:22.388
tonight did in the latest
national NBC/Wall Street Journal
poll without Biden. It's a

15:22.388 --> 15:25.725
race between Clinton
and Sanders.

15:25.725 --> 15:32.131
But, hypothetically, beam Biden
into the mix, and he would get
nearly one in five Democratic

15:32.131 --> 15:37.603
votes, taking some from Sanders,
but the biggest chunk would come
from camp Clinton. At the

15:37.603 --> 15:42.441
same time, Clinton faces
dropping favorability ratings,
meaning a debate without Biden
is

15:42.441 --> 15:45.344
a key opportunity for her.

15:45.344 --> 15:50.483
HILARY ROSEN: If Hillary does
really, really well and
Democrats end up rallying around

15:50.483 --> 15:55.154
her, you know, that might take
some of the air out of the Biden
balloon. And so there's

15:55.154 --> 15:56.589
a lot of pressure on Hillary.

15:56.589 --> 15:59.625
JOSEPH BIDEN: Things can
change in a heartbeat.

15:59.625 --> 16:03.129
LISA DESJARDINS: Adding to the
pressure on the race is the
super PAC Draft Biden.

16:03.129 --> 16:08.367
JOSEPH BIDEN: Six weeks after
the election, my hole world was
altered forever.

16:08.367 --> 16:13.439
LISA DESJARDINS: The group
created this emotional ad
stressing how Biden coped with
the death

16:13.439 --> 16:20.446
of his wife, daughter and now
son. Biden publicly asked the
group not to run it, and they
complied.

16:20.446 --> 16:25.618
It's part of the warm sentiment
and high favorabilities around
Biden right now, but that could
change,

16:25.618 --> 16:28.421
warns Democratic strategist
Rodell Mollineau.

16:28.421 --> 16:32.158
RODELL MOLLINEAU, Democratic
Strategist: Primary voters love
what they can't have. There's

16:32.158 --> 16:36.329
always the what if. What if this
person were to run or this
person were to run? And I think

16:36.329 --> 16:39.632
you're getting that right now
with Vice President Biden. I
think that it's a lot different,

16:39.632 --> 16:42.568
though, once you become
a declared candidate.

16:42.568 --> 16:47.707
LISA DESJARDINS: Mollineau
points to Biden's work on the
1994 crime bill, now criticized

16:47.707 --> 16:53.012
as propelling overincarceration.
In addition, Biden supports the
Trans-Pacific Partnership

16:53.012 --> 16:58.451
trade deal, unpopular with many
Democrats and opposed by Clinton
and Sanders.

16:58.451 --> 17:06.025
And, finally, with 36 years in
the Senate, Biden is an insider
in a year of the outsider.

17:06.025 --> 17:10.463
The vice president has indicated
it all comes down to a personal
decision, but some think

17:10.463 --> 17:13.699
tonight's debate might matter.

17:13.699 --> 17:18.037
RODELL MOLLINEAU: Should Vice
President Biden or his
consultants see a debate where
none

17:18.037 --> 17:21.774
of the candidates are truly
resonating with the voters or
the audience, that might be

17:21.774 --> 17:26.312
something that factors into his
decision as to whether or not he
runs.

17:26.312 --> 17:31.384
JUDY WOODRUFF: And Lisa joins us
now with the latest from the
Wynn Hotel in Las Vegas,

17:31.384 --> 17:33.185
the site of tonight's debate.

17:33.185 --> 17:35.655
Lisa, welcome.

17:35.655 --> 17:40.459
So, Vice President Biden is not
there. You have been talking to
a lot of people. What

17:40.459 --> 17:43.829
are they saying about the two
front-runners and what they need
to do tonight? What is

17:43.829 --> 17:47.266
their strategy, Hillary
Clinton and Bernie Sanders?

17:47.266 --> 17:50.636
LISA DESJARDINS: I
think that's right.

17:50.636 --> 17:56.275
Most people are looking for that
matchup tonight in particular.
Let's start with Bernie Sanders.

17:56.275 --> 17:59.378
We know from his campaign -- I
just talked to his campaign
spokeswoman, Simone Sanders,

17:59.378 --> 18:02.281
no relation. And she says that
he will not go on the attack,
that he's always stayed

18:02.281 --> 18:04.283
positive.

18:04.283 --> 18:08.587
However, Judy, it's just what
that means, because they are
saying that he will give

18:08.587 --> 18:13.759
differentiate himself from
Hillary Clinton. Expect him in
particular to talk about trade,

18:13.759 --> 18:16.562
and that is going to come back
to that interview that you had
with Hillary Clinton in which

18:16.562 --> 18:19.999
she announced that she opposes
the Trans-Pacific Partnership.

18:19.999 --> 18:24.670
Bernie Sanders, we expect, to
talk about his consistency,
point out that this is a
relatively

18:24.670 --> 18:30.576
new position for Hillary
Clinton. And Hillary Clinton,
her campaign is saying they want

18:30.576 --> 18:34.914
her to stay on message and also
stay positive, but same thing
here, Judy. Expect her to
differentiate

18:34.914 --> 18:38.584
herself, especially
on the issue of guns.

18:38.584 --> 18:42.455
Now, we can talk about the
debate stage, but the truth is,
Judy, the fight between these

18:42.455 --> 18:48.127
two Democrats has already
started in Las Vegas over
unions. Here, you see Hillary
Clinton

18:48.127 --> 18:53.899
yesterday speaking at a protest
